title: Evaluating the impact of misspecified spatial neighboring structures in Bayesian CAR models
summary: Misspecified spatial neighboring structures in Bayesian Conditional Autoregressive (CAR) models can significantly impact the accuracy and reliability of spatial analysis. This research evaluates the consequences of such misspecifications, examining how deviations from the true spatial dependencies affect model performance and subsequent inferences. Understanding these impacts is crucial for developing robust and accurate spatial models.

title: Smart investment in global childcare requires local solutions and a coordinated research agenda
summary: Effective childcare investment strategies must be tailored to specific community needs while also benefiting from a globally unified research framework. This approach allows for both localized solutions and the development of best practices that can be shared and adapted internationally. The coordinated research agenda will facilitate informed decision-making and maximize the impact of investments in childcare worldwide.

Global, regional, and national progress towards Sustainable Development Goal 3.2 for neonatal and child health: all-cause and cause-specific mortality findings from the Global Burden of Disease Study 2019
summary: The Global Burden of Disease Study 2019 assesses progress towards Sustainable Development Goal 3.2, focusing on neonatal and child mortality from all causes and specific causes at global, regional, and national levels. The study provides crucial data on mortality trends, informing interventions and policies aimed at reducing preventable deaths in children under five. This information is essential for tracking progress and identifying areas requiring targeted efforts to improve child survival worldwide.

title: “They talked to me rudely”. Women perspectives on quality of post-abortion care in public health facilities in Kenya
summary: Explores the experiences of women receiving post-abortion care in Kenyan public health facilities, highlighting disrespectful and rude treatment as a key concern impacting the quality of care. These findings suggest a need for interventions focused on improving provider communication and patient-centered care within these settings.

title: Why do most young women not take up contraceptives after post-abortion care? An ethnographic study on the effectiveness and quality of contraceptive counselling after PAC in Kilifi County, Kenya
summary: This ethnographic study investigates the low uptake of contraceptives among young women in Kilifi County, Kenya, following post-abortion care (PAC). It explores the effectiveness and quality of contraceptive counselling provided after PAC to understand the factors influencing contraceptive decisions. The research aims to identify potential barriers and inform strategies for improving contraceptive uptake in this population.

title: Impacts of two-year multisectoral cash plus programs on young adolescent girls' education, health and economic outcomes: Adolescent Girls Initiative-Kenya (AGI-K) randomized trial
summary: The Adolescent Girls Initiative-Kenya (AGI-K) randomized trial assessed the impacts of two-year multisectoral cash plus programs on various outcomes for young adolescent girls, including education, health, and economic empowerment. The study investigated the effectiveness of combined cash transfers and other interventions in improving the well-being of this vulnerable population. The findings contribute to evidence on the potential of such programs to address interconnected challenges faced by adolescent girls in Kenya.

title: Family Structure and Child Educational Attainment in the Slums of Nairobi, Kenya
summary: Investigates the correlation between family structure and children's educational attainment within the challenging context of Nairobi's slums. It likely examines various family structures (e.g., single-parent, extended family) and their impact on educational outcomes, potentially considering socioeconomic factors and access to resources. Understanding these relationships can inform targeted interventions to improve educational opportunities for children in vulnerable communities.
